Table 1: Performance of LLMs on ZebraLogic. The overall accuracy is calculated based on the number of puzzles solved correctly. We also report the accuracy on small, medium, large, and x-large groups based on the size of the search space (see Sec. 2.3).
The cell accuracy indicates the percentage of individual cells filled correctly. See Appx. A for more model results.
description: This table presents the performance of various Large Language Models (LLMs) on the ZebraLogic benchmark.  It shows the overall accuracy of each model in solving logic grid puzzles, broken down by puzzle complexity (small, medium, large, x-large, categorized by search space size).  Additionally, it provides the cell accuracy, which is the percentage of individual cells correctly filled in the solution grids.  For a more comprehensive view of the model results, refer to Appendix A.

caption:
Table 2: 
Comparison of various test-time compute scaling methods applied to GPT-4o and GPT-4o-mini. We evaluate several approaches: BoN-Oracle (selection using oracle knowledge to verify correct answers among samples), BoN-RM (selection using a reward model), Majority-Voting (selecting the most common answer across samples), and Self-Verify (using multi-turn prompting for self-reflection and correction, with and without oracle knowledge).
We use \faLightbulb to denote the use of oracle knowledge.
description: This table presents a comparison of different test-time compute scaling methods applied to the GPT-4 and GPT-4-mini language models.  It evaluates the effectiveness of four approaches: Best-of-N sampling with oracle knowledge (BoN-Oracle), Best-of-N sampling with a reward model (BoN-RM), majority voting, and a self-verification method that involves multi-turn prompting for self-reflection and correction. The results are shown with and without oracle knowledge, providing insights into how different techniques impact the models' performance on logical reasoning tasks.
